# swayidle configuration
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Two parsing rules to remember (see sway-desktop-tuning skill, "CRITICAL" section):
#   1. Each event command must be a single-token path to a script file.
#      Inline `sh -c "..."` gets truncated to just `sh` and the rest is lost.
#   2. `timeout` and its `resume` MUST be on the SAME line. Config is parsed
#      line-by-line, no multi-line continuation.
#
# All events below delegate to a unified `sway-session` script (see
# templates/sway-session.py) — this user's strong preference is one
# unified entry point with subcommands, not scattered helper scripts.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# 60s after no activity: mark the user idle so the daemon skips its 5-min save
# (covers "user walked away" case; the save will resume on next activity)
timeout 60 ~/Scripts/sway-session --mark-idle resume ~/Scripts/sway-session --mark-active

# 60 minutes after no activity: turn off the external monitor to save power
# (always pair with a resume action — otherwise the screen stays black forever)
timeout 3600 ~/Scripts/sway-session --screen-off resume ~/Scripts/sway-session --screen-on

# ── Add more events here as needed. Common additions: ───────────────
# Lock screen on idle (requires swaylock):
#   timeout 300 ~/Scripts/sway-session --lock resume ~/Scripts/sway-session --unlock
#
# Suspend on long idle:
#   timeout 1800 ~/Scripts/sway-session --suspend
#
# Tell logind about session idle (so logind's IdleAction kicks in):
#   idlehint 300
#   (note: idlehint takes no resume — it auto-clears on user activity)
